    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="113"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d113">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.811/127.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Reinsch</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-18">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 18, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your telegram of May 9. Chang Chien has wired that as preliminary surveys had
                    been carefully made by his engineers, supplementary survey ought not to cost
                    more than $25,000. However, Cabinet has decided to assume responsibility for
                    repayment of cost up to $50,000 gold. Government believes that judgment as to
                    whether the work is practicable could be formed after expenditure of that
                    amount; further supplementary surveys regarding details could then be paid out
                    of proceeds of the loans when raised.</p>
                <p>Your May 13. As Chang Chien is still absent in the south, such negotiations would
                    be difficult and lengthy. Do you desire to have me suggest that he return for
                    conference or will negotiations be continued in the United States?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
